'''Nathan Benjamin Aké''' ({{IPA|nl|'naːtɑn 'aːkeː|lang}};<ref>{{cite web |date=25 June 2024 |title=Netherlands TEAM TALK ft. GAKPO, AKÉ, SIMONS & WEGHORST {{!}} EURO 2024 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ziji8N3NylE&t=12s |access-date=7 June 2025 |via=YouTube |publisher=[[UEFA]] |language=nl}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=30 September 2019 |title="IK ZOU OOK WEL EENS ZO GROOT WILLEN ZIJN" {{!}} NATHAN AKÉ BEANTWOORDT ALLE VRAGEN {{!}} ZAPPSPORT |trans-title="I WOULD LIKE TO BE THAT BIG TOO" {{!}} NATHAN AKÉ ANSWERS ALL QUESTIONS {{!}} ZAPPSPORT |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g9W7ys6EwMM&t=15s |access-date=7 June 2025 |via=YouTube |publisher=[[Zappsport]] |language=nl}}</ref> born 18 February 1995) is a Dutch professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[centre-back]] or [[left-back]] for {{English football updater|ManchesC}} club [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] and the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands national team]].

==Early life==
Nathan Benjamin Aké<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fdp.fifa.org/assetspublic/ce44/pdf/SquadLists-English.pdf |title=Squad List: FIFA World Cup Qatar 2022: Netherlands (NED) |publisher=FIFA |page=20 |date=18 December 2022 |access-date=25 June 2023 |archive-date=15 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221115074706/https://fdp.fifa.org/assetspublic/ce44/pdf/SquadLists-English.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref> was born on 18 February 1995<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/player/_/id/159248/nathan-ake |title=Nathan Aké: Overview |publisher=ESPN |access-date=31 July 2020 |archive-date=5 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210605050857/https://www.espn.co.uk/football/player/_/id/159248/nathan-ake |url-status=live }}</ref> in [[The Hague]], South Holland,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/nathan-ak%c3%a9-240454/ |title=Nathan Aké |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |access-date=31 July 2020}}</ref> to an Ivorian father, and a Dutch mother.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nathan Ake Childhood Story Plus Untold Biography Facts |date=5 August 2018 |url=https://lifebogger.com/nathan-ake-childhood-story-plus-untold-biography-facts/ |access-date=3 December 2022 |archive-date=3 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190603120849/https://lifebogger.com/nathan-ake-childhood-story-plus-untold-biography-facts/ |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/apr/15/nathan-ake-watford-jose-mourinho-chelsea? |title=Nathan Aké on Watford, Mourinho and the Chelsea loanees' WhatsApp group |newspaper=The Guardian |access-date=17 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chelseafc.com/news/latest-news/2017/05/near-and-far--nathan-ake1.html |title=Near and Far: Nathan Ake |publisher=Chelsea F.C. |access-date=3 May 2017}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Chelsea===
====Early career====
Aké agreed to join the [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] youth system from [[Feyenoord]] in 2010 at age 15.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/dec/22/chelsea-nathan-ake-feyenoord |title=Feyenoord lash Premier League after Chelsea land 15-year-old prospect |first=Dominic |last=Fifield |date=22 December 2010|access-date=1 January 2020 |newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> He had played at Feyenoord since age 12 after joining the club from [[ADO Den Haag]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vvwilhelmus.nl/nieuws/2011/december/nathan-ak%C3%A9,-oud-wilhelmus-jeugd-speler,-definitief-naar-chelsea-fc/ |title=Nathan Aké, oud Wilhelmus Jeugd speler, definitief naar Chelsea FC |publisher=V.V. Wilhelmus |access-date=16 May 2013 |language=nl |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129063009/http://www.vvwilhelmus.nl/nieuws/2011/december/nathan-ak%C3%A9,-oud-wilhelmus-jeugd-speler,-definitief-naar-chelsea-fc/ |archive-date=29 November 2014}}</ref>

[[File:Nathan Ake 2013.jpg|thumb|upright|Aké playing for [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in 2013]]

Aké made his [[Premier League]] debut on 26 December 2012 against [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] as a 17-year-old, replacing [[Juan Mata]] in added time at the end of a 1–0 win at [[Carrow Road]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Phillips |first=Owen |title=Norwich 0–1 Chelsea |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/20779143 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=26 December 2012 |archive-date=1 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130101180041/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20779143 |url-status=live }}</ref> He made his first start for the club in the [[2012–13 FA Cup|FA Cup]] on 27 February 2013 in a 2–0 win against [[EFL Championship|Championship]] team [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/21515665 "Middlesbrough 0–2 Chelsea"]  BBC Sport. 27 February 2013. Retrieved 27 February 2013.</ref> He was chosen to start in a defensive midfield position for Chelsea in the second leg of their [[2012–13 UEFA Europa League|UEFA Europa League]] quarter-final clash with [[FC Rubin Kazan|Rubin Kazan]] in Russia on 11 April, a match that finished in a 3–2 loss but resulted in a 5–4 aggregate victory.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/apr/11/rubin-kazan-chelsea-europa-league |title=Chelsea struggle to finish off Rubin Kazan but reach semi-finals |newspaper=The Guardian |date=11 April 2013 |archive-date=9 June 2020 |access-date=15 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200609081826/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/apr/11/rubin-kazan-chelsea-europa-league |url-status=live }}</ref> Aké was an unused substitute for Chelsea in the [[2013 UEFA Europa League final]] against [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] at the [[Amsterdam Arena]] on 16 May, which Chelsea won 2–1.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/benfica-vs-chelsea/teams/286317 |title=Europa League (Sky Sports) |website=Sky Sports|access-date=1 January 2020}}</ref> He was voted Chelsea's Young Player of the Year on 16 May,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chelseafc.com/javaImages/94/36/0,,10268~11941524,00.jpg |title=<image>  |access-date=16 May 2013 |publisher=Chelsea F.C. |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131116205013/http://www.chelseafc.com/javaImages/94/36/0,,10268~11941524,00.jpg |archive-date=16 November 2013}}</ref> and made his first Premier League start three days later in the 2–1 win against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] on the last matchday of the season.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}

On 8 August 2013, Aké signed a new five-year contract with Chelsea, lasting until 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chelseafc.com/news-article/article/3342358/title/new-deal-for-ake |title=New Deal for Aké |publisher=Chelsea F.C. |date=8 August 2013 |access-date=9 August 2013 |archive-date=28 August 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130828034928/http://www.chelseafc.com/news-article/article/3342358/title/new-deal-for-ake |url-status=live }}</ref> Following his permanent promotion to the first team, on 21 October 2014, Aké made his [[2014–15 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]] debut from the substitutes' bench, coming into the match for [[Cesc Fàbregas]] in the 60th minute during a 6–0 home win over [[NK Maribor|Maribor]], and provided an assist for [[Eden Hazard]]'s second goal.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/29362738 |title=Didier Drogba scored his first goal since rejoining Chelsea as they recorded their biggest Champions League win with a dominant victory against Maribor at Stamford Bridge. |website=BBC Sport |date=21 October 2014 |access-date=21 October 2014 |archive-date=23 January 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160123092742/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/29362738 |url-status=live }}</ref>

====Loan spells====
On 25 March 2015, Aké was loaned to Championship club [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] for one month,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/article/royals-sign-nathan-ake-on-loan-from-chelsea-2358756.aspx |title=Royals Sign Nathan Ake on Loan |publisher=Reading F.C. |access-date=25 March 2015 |archive-date=1 September 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160901002216/http://www.readingfc.co.uk//news/article/royals-sign-nathan-ake-on-loan-from-chelsea-2358756.aspx |url-status=live }}</ref> making his first of five appearances against [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] in a 1–1 draw ten days later.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sportsmole.co.uk/football/reading/team-news/team-news-nathan-ake-handed-reading-debut_215094.html |title=Nathan Ake handed Reading debut |website=Sportsmole.co.uk |access-date=4 April 2015 |archive-date=18 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418063107/https://www.sportsmole.co.uk/football/reading/team-news/team-news-nathan-ake-handed-reading-debut_215094.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Although he only made one league appearance for Chelsea the entire season, as a substitute in a 3–0 loss at [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] on 18 May,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/32686137 |title=West Brom inflicted a third league defeat of the season on champions Chelsea in an eventful game at The Hawthorns. |website=BBC Sport |date=18 May 2015 |access-date=19 May 2015 |archive-date=25 December 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151225064743/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/32686137 |url-status=live }}</ref> manager [[José Mourinho]] said Aké would receive a winner's medal for his contribution to the team [[2014–15 Chelsea F.C. season|that season]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.com/chelsea/story/2450893/jose-mourinho-every-chelsea-player-to-get-prem-medal |title=Every Chelsea player to get a Premier League medal says Jose Mourinho |website=ESPN FC |date=15 May 2015 |access-date=1 January 2020 |archive-date=4 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170804223651/http://www.espnfc.com/chelsea/story/2450893/jose-mourinho-every-chelsea-player-to-get-prem-medal |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 14 August 2015, Aké completed a season-long loan move to newly promoted Premier League club [[Watford F.C.|Watford]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.watfordfc.com/news/article/150814-nathan-ake-signs-for-watford-fc-from-chelsea-2619925.aspx |title=OFFICIAL: Aké Joins Hornets On Loan |publisher=Watford F.C. |access-date=14 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160221045212/http://www.watfordfc.com/news/article/150814-nathan-ake-signs-for-watford-fc-from-chelsea-2619925.aspx |archive-date=21 February 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref> after having signed a new five-year contract with Chelsea.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chelseafc.com/news/latest-news/2015/08/new-deal-for-ake.html |title=New deal for Aké |publisher=Chelsea F.C. |access-date=14 August 2015 |archive-date=16 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150816191108/http://www.chelseafc.com/news/latest-news/2015/08/new-deal-for-ake.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Eleven days later, he made his debut for the Hornets in a [[2015–16 Football League Cup|League Cup]] second round match against [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]], which ended in a 1–0 defeat for his team.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/33969908 |title=Championship Preston reached round three of the Capital One Cup as Marnick Vermijl's goal saw off Premier League Watford, who finished with 10 men |website=BBC Sport |access-date=25 August 2015 |archive-date=13 December 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151213222611/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/33969908 |url-status=live }}</ref> Aké played his first Premier League match coming off the substitutes' bench against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] 19 September 2015, helping Watford hold on for a 2–1 win.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2015/09/19/england/premier-league/newcastle-united-football-club/watford-football-club/2043102/ |title=Newcastle United vs. Watford 1 – 2 (9/19/15) |website=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group |date=19 September 2015 |access-date=21 February 2018 |archive-date=18 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418063145/https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2015/09/19/england/premier-league/newcastle-united-football-club/watford-football-club/2043102/ |url-status=live }}</ref> He scored his first senior goal on 20 December, opening a 3–0 win over [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] at [[Vicarage Road]] in the fourth minute, after goalkeeper [[Ádám Bogdán]] dropped a corner kick.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35086289 |title=Watford 3–0 Liverpool |date=20 December 2015 |access-date=1 January 2020 |website=BBC Sport |archive-date=12 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221112135708/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35086289 |url-status=live }}</ref>

During his time with the Hertfordshire side, manager [[Quique Sánchez Flores]] primarily deployed Aké as a [[left-back]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Smith |first1=Adam |title=Nathan Ake: How would Bournemouth defender improve Manchester City? |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/21476/11883642/nathan-ake-how-would-bournemouth-defender-improve-manchester-city |website=Sky Sports |access-date=20 January 2021 |date=6 August 2020 |archive-date=30 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221030103222/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/21476/11883642/nathan-ake-how-would-bournemouth-defender-improve-manchester-city |url-status=live }}</ref> His performance and work ethic earned him Watford's Young Player of the Season award.<ref name="Watford Award">{{cite web |last1=Barlow |first1=Matt |title=Watford: END OF SEASON AWARDS: Gomes Named 2015/16 Player Of The Season |url=http://www.watfordfc.com/news/article/160517-watford-fc-end-of-season-awards-winners-3116857.aspx |access-date=5 July 2016 |publisher=Watford F.C. |date=18 May 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160603055221/http://www.watfordfc.com/news/article/160517-watford-fc-end-of-season-awards-winners-3116857.aspx |archive-date=3 June 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref>

On 29 June 2016, Aké joined [[AFC Bournemouth|Bournemouth]] on loan for the [[2016–17 AFC Bournemouth season|2016–17 season]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Ake loaned to the Cherries |url=http://www.chelseafc.com/news/latest-news/2016/06/ake-loaned-to-the-cherries.html?extcmp=SOCIA_TW_ENG_ARTICLES |publisher=Chelsea F.C. |date=29 June 2016 |access-date=29 June 2016 |archive-date=9 June 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200609091840/https://www.chelseafc.com/news/latest-news/2016/06/ake-loaned-to-the-cherries.html?extcmp=SOCIA_TW_ENG_ARTICLES |url-status=live }}</ref> On 21 August, he made his Bournemouth debut in a 1–0 away defeat against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]], replacing [[Jordon Ibe]] following teammate [[Harry Arter]]'s dismissal after a challenge on [[Cheikhou Kouyaté]].<ref>{{cite news |title=West Ham United 1–0 Bournemouth |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37075120 |website=BBC Sport |date=21 August 2016 |access-date=21 August 2016 |archive-date=9 June 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200609081826/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37075120 |url-status=live }}</ref> Following the defeat to West Ham, Aké made his full debut against [[Morecambe F.C.|Morecambe]] in the [[2016–17 EFL Cup#Second round|second round of the EFL Cup]] on 24 August.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.afcb.co.uk/news/article/2016-17/team-news-morecambe-vs-afc-bournemouth-efl-cup-3270153.aspx |title=Team news: Morecambe vs AFC Bournemouth – Ten changes from West Ham United defeat |date=24 August 2016 |publisher=AFC Bournemouth |access-date=25 August 2016 |archive-date=12 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221112133454/https://www.afcb.co.uk/news/article/2016-17/team-news-morecambe-vs-afc-bournemouth-efl-cup-3270153.aspx/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> On 19 November, in his first Premier League start, Aké scored his first goal for Bournemouth in a 1–0 away victory over [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/37959843 |title=Stoke City 0–1 Bournemouth |date=19 November 2016 |website=BBC Sport |archive-date=18 April 2020 |access-date=11 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418063159/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/37959843 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 4 December 2016, Bournemouth played Liverpool and overturned a 3–1 deficit with 15 minutes to go to win the match 4–3; Aké scoring the winning goal in the 93rd minute, his third Premier League goal and the second against Liverpool.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bournemouth 4–3 Liverpool |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38121184 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=14 January 2022 |archive-date=12 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221112140455/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38121184 |url-status=live }}</ref>

====Return to Chelsea====
Aké was recalled by Chelsea on 8 January 2017,<ref>{{cite news |title=Nathan Ake: Chelsea recall defender early from Bournemouth loan |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38544921 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=8 January 2017 |archive-date=12 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221112135706/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38544921 |url-status=live }}</ref> making his first appearance for the club since the recall on 28 January in a 4–0 [[2016–17 FA Cup|FA Cup]] fourth round victory over fellow West London club [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Phil |last=Lythell |date=28 January 2017 |access-date=28 January 2017 |title=Willian leads impressive Chelsea to big FA Cup fourth round win vs. Brentford |website=ESPN FC |url=http://www.espnfc.co.uk/club/chelsea/363/blog/post/3048506/willian-leads-impressive-chelsea-to-big-fa-cup-fourth-round-win-vs-brentford |archive-date=11 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190811160710/http://www.espnfc.co.uk/club/chelsea/363/blog/post/3048506/willian-leads-impressive-chelsea-to-big-fa-cup-fourth-round-win-vs-brentford |url-status=live }}</ref> He was also selected to start in Chelsea's 2–0 win over [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] in the fifth round of the same competition on 18 February.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/38940092 |title=Wolverhampton Wanderers 0–2 Chelsea |date=18 February 2017 |website=BBC Sport |archive-date=18 April 2020 |access-date=11 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418063218/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/38940092 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 22 April 2017, Aké started alongside [[David Luiz]] and [[César Azpilicueta]] in central defence in Chelsea's 4–2 FA Cup semi-final victory over rivals [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] at [[Wembley Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39604653 |title=Chelsea 4–2 Tottenham |date=22 April 2017 |website=BBC Sport |archive-date=13 June 2018 |access-date=11 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613040448/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39604653 |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Bournemouth===
On 30 June 2017, Aké signed a contract with Premier League club Bournemouth on a permanent basis for a club record transfer fee of £20&nbsp;million, with the player officially re-joining the club the following day, when the 2017 transfer window opened.<ref name="BBC_30Jun2017">{{cite news |title=Nathan Ake: Bournemouth sign Chelsea defender for a club record fee |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40454293 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=30 June 2017 |date=30 June 2017 |archive-date=18 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418063224/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40454293 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 21 July, it was reported his former club Chelsea had inserted a buy-back clause for Aké in his transfer contract.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/transfers/nathan-ake-chelsea-bournemouth-transfer-buy-back-clause-a7814166.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220618/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/transfers/nathan-ake-chelsea-bournemouth-transfer-buy-back-clause-a7814166.html |archive-date=18 June 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |title=Chelsea are selling Nathan Ake to Bournemouth for £20m but are already thinking about buying him back |date=29 June 2017 |newspaper=The Independent |access-date=1 January 2020}}</ref>

In his first season after joining Bournemouth permanently, Aké was named as both the club's Players' Player of the Season and Fans' Player of the Season for [[2017–18 AFC Bournemouth season|2017–18]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.afcb.co.uk/news/2018/May/9/francis-ake-up-there-with-europe-s-best|title=Francis – Ake up there with Europe's best|date=9 May 2018|access-date=23 June 2025|website=AFC Bournemouth}}</ref> He played in all 38 of the team's [[2017–18 Premier League|Premier League]] matches,<ref name=class>{{cite web|url=https://www.afcb.co.uk/news/2020/August/6/nathan-ake-a-class-act|title=Nathan Ake: A class act|date=6 August 2020|access-date=23 June 2025|website=AFC Bournemouth}}</ref> scoring in a 3–3 draw at home to [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/42360011|title=Bournemouth 3–3 West Ham United|date=26 December 2017|access-date=23 June 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> and in a 3–0 away win at his former club Chelsea.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/42799048|title=Chelsea 0–3 Bournemouth|date=31 January 2019|access-date=23 June 2025|website=BBC Sport|archive-date=13 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180713024040/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/42799048|url-status=live}}</ref>

In [[2018–19 AFC Bournemouth season|2018–19]], Aké again appeared in all of Bournemouth's [[2018–19 Premier League|Premier League]] matches,<ref name=class/> scoring four times.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.afcb.co.uk/news/2019/May/18/ake-scoops-player-of-the-month-for-may|title=Ake scoops Player of the Month for May|date=18 May 2019|access-date=23 June 2025|website=AFC Bournemouth}}</ref> On 4 May 2019, Aké scored a stoppage time goal against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] to give Bournemouth a 1–0 win in their final home match of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48075160|title=Bournemouth 1–0 Tottenham: Nine-man Spurs fail to secure top-four spot|date=4 May 2019|access-date=23 June 2025|website=BBC Sport|archive-date=6 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190506110658/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48075160|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 3 December 2019, Aké captained Bournemouth for the first time in a 1–0 loss at [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bournemouthecho.co.uk/sport/18083516.eddie-howe-honoured-give-nathan-ake-captains-armband-backs-future-afc-bournemouth-skipper/?action=add_comment|title=Eddie Howe 'honoured' to give Nathan Ake the captain's armband and backs him to be a future AFC Bournemouth skipper|date=6 December 2019|access-date=23 June 2025|website=Bournemouth Echo}}</ref> Four days later, he suffered a hamstring injury in a 3–0 loss at Liverpool, keeping him out of the team for six matches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/50780851|title=Nathan Ake: Bournemouth defender faces up to six weeks out – Eddie Howe|date=13 December 2019|access-date=23 June 2025|website=BBC Sport|archive-date=31 August 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220831095958/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/50780851|url-status=live}}</ref> A groin injury sustained in a 4–1 win over [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] on 15 July 2020 ended his [[2019–20 AFC Bournemouth season|season]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11743/12027318/nathan-ake-set-to-miss-rest-of-season-with-injury-in-huge-blow-for-bournemouth|title=Nathan Ake set to miss rest of season with injury in huge blow for Bournemouth|date=12 July 2020|access-date=23 June 2025|website=Sky Sports|archive-date=4 August 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240804080028/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11743/12027318/nathan-ake-set-to-miss-rest-of-season-with-injury-in-huge-blow-for-bournemouth|url-status=live}}</ref> On 26 July, on the final day of the [[2019–20 Premier League]] season, Bournemouth were relegated to the [[EFL Championship]] after [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] drew with West Ham United.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/53460590|title=Everton 1–3 Bournemouth: Cherries relegated despite win|date=26 July 2020|access-date=23 June 2025|website=BBC Sport|archive-date=2 September 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200902205339/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/53460590|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Manchester City===
On 5 August 2020, Aké signed for [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] on a five-year contract for £41&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mancity.com/news/mens/nathan-ake-signs-63732245 |title=Nathan Ake completes City switch |first=Rob |last=Pollard |publisher=Manchester City F.C. |access-date=5 August 2020 |archive-date=5 August 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200805183548/https://www.mancity.com/news/mens/nathan-ake-signs-63732245 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11679/12043190/nathan-ake-manchester-city-sign-defender-from-bournemouth |title=Nathan Ake: Manchester City sign defender from Bournemouth |website=Sky Sports |access-date=10 April 2023 |archive-date=25 July 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230725154022/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11679/12043190/nathan-ake-manchester-city-sign-defender-from-bournemouth |url-status=live }}</ref> He started and debuted in City's first game of the season on 21 September, winning 3–1 against Wolverhampton Wanderers away from home in the Premier League.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Brennan |first=Stuart |date=21 September 2020 |title=Man City player ratings vs Wolves |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/man-city-wolves-player-ratings-18973408 |access-date=21 September 2020 |website=Manchester Evening News |archive-date=29 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211229005204/https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/man-city-wolves-player-ratings-18973408 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 27 September 2020, he scored his first goal for City in a 2–5 home defeat against [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/54222449 |title=Manchester City 2–5 Leicester City |website=BBC Sport |date=27 September 2020 |access-date=27 September 2020 |archive-date=14 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201014214821/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/54222449 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 3 November 2020, Aké made his [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] debut for City in a 3–0 home win over [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]] in the [[2020–21 UEFA Champions League group stage#Group C|group stage]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/54784118 |title=Manchester City 3–0 Olympiakos |date=3 November 2020 |website=BBC Sport |archive-date=8 November 2020 |access-date=3 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201108174429/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/54784118 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Aké scored his first Champions League goal on 15 September 2021 in a 6–3 win against [[RB Leipzig]]. He revealed afterwards that his father, who had been terminally ill, had died shortly after the time he scored.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58588730 |title=Nathan Ake: Manchester City defender's father died minutes after first UEFA Champions League goal |website=BBC Sport |date=16 September 2021 |access-date=17 September 2021 |archive-date=16 September 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210916165246/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/58588730 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 10 June 2023, he was selected in the starting line-up for Manchester City in the [[2023 UEFA Champions League final|Champions League final]] against [[Inter Milan]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mancity.com/news/mens/manchester-city-v-inter-champions-league-final-team-news-and-tactics-63822010 |title=Ake and Ederson return as City make two changes for Champions League final |publisher=Manchester City F.C. |date=10 June 2023 |access-date=23 June 2023 |archive-date=26 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230626214850/https://www.mancity.com/news/mens/manchester-city-v-inter-champions-league-final-team-news-and-tactics-63822010 |url-status=live }}</ref> which his club won 1–0 to complete their continental treble.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/65845807 |title=Manchester City 1–0 Inter Milan |website=BBC Sport |date=10 June 2023 |access-date=23 June 2023 |archive-date=11 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230611095758/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/65845807 |url-status=live }}</ref> A month later, on 29 July, he extended his contract until 2027.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mancity.com/news/mens/nathan-ake-signs-new-manchester-city-contract-63826211 |title=Ake pens new City deal! |publisher=Manchester City F.C. |date=29 July 2023}}</ref>

On 28 September 2023, Aké captained Manchester City for the first time in a 0–1 defeat against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] in the third round of the [[2023–24 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=VAVEL.com |date=28 September 2023 |title=Goal and Highlights: Newcastle 1–0 Manchester City in Carabao Cup 2023 {{!}} 28 September 2023 |url=https://www.vavel.com/en-us/soccer/2023/09/27/1157250-newcastle-vs-manchester-city-live-updates-score-stream-info-lineups-and-how-to-watch-carabao-cup-match.html |access-date=2023-09-29 |website=VAVEL |language=en-us}}</ref>

On 26 January 2024, Aké became Manchester City's first player in history to score at the [[Tottenham Hotspur Stadium]], in a 1–0 [[2023–24 FA Cup#Fourth round proper|fourth round]] victory over [[Tottenham Hotspur]] in the [[FA Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68097502 |title=Tottenham Hotspur 0–1 Manchester City: Nathan Ake scores late winner |website=BBC Sport |date=26 January 2024 |access-date=26 January 2024 |archive-date=16 May 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240516130408/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68097502 |url-status=live }}</ref>

==International career==
Aké has represented the Netherlands at every youth level since his under-15 debut in 2009, making 54 appearances in total.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/nathan-ake/182930/ |title=N. Aké |website=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group |access-date=26 September 2014 |archive-date=18 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418063252/https://int.soccerway.com/players/nathan-ake/182930/ |url-status=live }}</ref> He was a member of the squads that won the [[UEFA European Under-17 Championship]] in [[2011 UEFA European Under-17 Championship|2011]] and [[2012 UEFA European Under-17 Championship|2012]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/under17/news/0252-0ce01a2ce5e4-bebe83bf10a7-1000--captain-ake-learns-from-chelsea-stars/ |title=Captain Aké learns from Chelsea stars |date=14 May 2012 |publisher=UEFA |access-date=14 May 2012 |archive-date=14 December 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241214045416/https://www.uefa.com/under17/news/0252-0ce01a2ce5e4-bebe83bf10a7-1000--captain-ake-learns-from-chelsea-stars/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Aké was also eligible to represent the [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast]] through his father Moise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2896/premier-league/2017/05/02/35150672/chelsea-star-ake-could-snub-netherlands-for-ivory-coast|title=Chelsea star Ake could snub Netherlands for Ivory Coast|website=Goal (website)|publisher=Perform Group|access-date=3 May 2017|archive-date=2 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170502205810/http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2896/premier-league/2017/05/02/35150672/chelsea-star-ake-could-snub-netherlands-for-ivory-coast|url-status=live}}</ref> On 31 May 2017, he made his senior international debut in a friendly match against [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]], who were beaten 1–2 by the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.beinsports.com/en/football/news/morocco-1-netherlands-2-promes-and-depay-sh-1/556727|title=Morocco 1–2 Netherlands: Promes and Depay shine as 10-man visitors hold on|website=[[BeIN Sports]]|date=31 May 2017|access-date=1 January 2020|archive-date=12 November 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221112134949/https://www.beinsports.com/en/football/news/morocco-1-netherlands-2-promes-and-depay-sh-1/556727|url-status=live}}</ref> He scored his first goal in a 1–1 draw with [[Italy national football team|Italy]] on 4 June 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Dutch delight as Cherries defender Nathan Ake scores his first senior international goal|url=https://www.bournemouthecho.co.uk/news/16269956.Dutch_delight_as_Cherries_defender_Nathan_Ake_scores_his_first_senior_international_goal/|newspaper=[[Bournemouth Daily Echo]]|date=5 June 2018|access-date=1 April 2025}}</ref> Aké was a member of the Netherlands squad for [[UEFA Euro 2020]], appearing twice as a substitute in [[UEFA Euro 2020 Group C|group]] matches against [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2021/jun/13/netherlands-ukraine-euro-2020-match-report|title=Dumfries heads Netherlands to 3–2 win and denies Ukraine's dream comeback|date=14 June 2021|access-date=5 November 2023|website=The Guardian|archive-date=5 November 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231105142555/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2021/jun/13/netherlands-ukraine-euro-2020-match-report|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Austria national football team|Austria]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Aké plays final third as Dutch secure knockout berth|url=https://www.mancity.com/news/mens/manchester-citys-nathan-ake-plays-in-2-0-win-over-austria-63759560|publisher=Manchester City F.C.|date=17 June 2021|access-date=5 November 2023}}</ref>

Aké started all five matches for the Netherlands at the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] as they reached the quarter-finals, where they were knocked out by eventual winner [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] in a [[penalty shootout]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/fifaplus/en/articles/lionel-messi-jurrien-timber-nathan-ake-virgil-van-dijk-louis-van-gaal-netherlands-argentina-fifa-world-cup-qatar-2022|title=Dutch trio up for Messi test|access-date=5 November 2023|date=8 December 2022|publisher=FIFA|archive-date=5 November 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231105145328/https://www.fifa.com/fifaplus/en/articles/lionel-messi-jurrien-timber-nathan-ake-virgil-van-dijk-louis-van-gaal-netherlands-argentina-fifa-world-cup-qatar-2022|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/fifa-world-cup/netherlands-argentina-directo/2022/12/09/01_0117_20221209_366_632.html|title=Netherlands 2–2 Argentina (3–4 pens): Lautaro scores and Argentina are through on penalties|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|publisher=Unidad Editorial|date=9 December 2022|access-date=5 November 2023|archive-date=17 March 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230317180135/https://www.marca.com/en/football/fifa-world-cup/netherlands-argentina-directo/2022/12/09/01_0117_20221209_366_632.html|url-status=live}}</ref> In June 2023, he was part of the Netherlands' squad for the [[2023 UEFA Nations League Finals]], where he started at left back against both [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] in the semi-final and [[Italy national football team|Italy]] in the third place play-off.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefanationsleague/match/2035581--netherlands-vs-croatia/|title=Netherlands vs Croatia|date=15 June 2023|access-date=7 June 2024|publisher=UEFA}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefanationsleague/match/2035583--netherlands-vs-italy/|title=Netherlands vs Italy|date=18 June 2023|access-date=7 June 2024|publisher=UEFA|archive-date=14 January 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240114105451/https://www.uefa.com/uefanationsleague/match/2035583--netherlands-vs-italy/|url-status=live}}</ref> On 29 May 2024, Aké was named in the Netherlands' squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]].<ref>{{Cite web|first=Callum|last=Davies|title=Netherlands Euro 2024 squad: Georginio Wijnaldum and Daley Blind retained|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5526712/2024/05/29/netherlands-euro-2024-squad-confirmed/|website=[[The Athletic]]|date=29 May 2024|access-date=7 June 2024|archive-date=30 May 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240530082146/https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5526712/2024/05/29/netherlands-euro-2024-squad-confirmed/|url-status=live}}</ref>

==Style of play==
Aké has been praised for his versatility, passing range, reading of the game, ability to play at [[Full-back (association football)|full back]], [[centre-back]], and in [[defensive midfield]], which has been attributed to a good work ethic, professionalism and gifted technique. His calmness on the ball and appearance have led to comparisons to former Dutch international player [[Ruud Gullit]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/i-follow-my-own-path-ake-reveals-drogba-advice-not-the-reason-he-/1vo5c0s9a192h1uqegmwvd68zj |title='I follow my own path' – Ake reveals Drogba advice not the reason he signed for Chelsea |website=Goal (website) |publisher=Perform Group |access-date=1 January 2020 |archive-date=20 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231020150518/https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/i-follow-my-own-path-ake-reveals-drogba-advice-not-the-reason-he-/1vo5c0s9a192h1uqegmwvd68zj |url-status=live }}</ref>

Aké is a strong and physical defender who is comfortable in one-on-one situations and is adept at making tackles and interceptions.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web |title=Nathan Ake's role at Man City: Pep Guardiola on 'karma' for defender as he emerges as key man on and off the pitch |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12839319/nathan-akes-role-at-man-city-pep-guardiola-on-karma-for-defender-as-he-emerges-as-key-man-on-and-off-the-pitch |access-date=2023-09-22 |website=Sky Sports |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite web |last=Arnold |first=Rebekka |date=4 May 2023 |title=Man City: Nathan Ake was the unsung hero vs West Ham |url=https://www.footballfancast.com/manchester-city-nathan-ake-pep-guardiola-premier-league-performance-analysis-latest-news-mcfc/ |access-date=2023-09-22 |website=FootballFanCast |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":3">{{Cite web |date=8 August 2020 |title=How could Nathan Ake fit at Manchester City 2020/21 – scout report |url=https://totalfootballanalysis.com/competitions/premier-league/nathan-ake-fit-manchester-city-2020-21-scout-report-tactical-analysis-tactics |access-date=2023-09-22 |website=Total Football Analysis Magazine |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=":4">{{Cite web |title=Nathan Ake: How would Bournemouth defender improve Manchester City? |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/21476/11883642/nathan-ake-how-would-bournemouth-defender-improve-manchester-city |access-date=2023-09-22 |website=Sky Sports |language=en |archive-date=30 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221030103222/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/21476/11883642/nathan-ake-how-would-bournemouth-defender-improve-manchester-city |url-status=live }}</ref> He is also strong in the air and is capable of winning aerial duels in both boxes.<ref name=":1" /><ref name=":3" /><ref name=":4" /><ref name=":5">{{Cite web |last=Marshall |first=Tyrone |date=28 January 2023 |title=Nathan Ake proved Pep Guardiola was right in Man City win vs Arsenal |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/man-city-vs-arsenal-goals-26095106 |access-date=2023-09-22 |website=Manchester Evening News |language=en}}</ref> Ake's reading of the game is another key part of his style of play, and he is often in the right position to make crucial blocks and clearances.<ref name=":1" /><ref name=":2" /><ref name=":3" /><ref name=":5" />

==Personal life==
Aké is a [[Teetotalism|teetotaller]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/jul/30/premier-league-2018-19-preview-bournemouth |title=Premier League 2018–19 preview No 2: Bournemouth |first=Ben |last=Fisher |date=30 July 2018 |newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref>

In the summer of 2022, Aké married Kaylee Ramman, who gave birth to their first child the year after.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Law |first1=Matt |title=Nathan Ake interview: 'My wife had our baby induced early so I could meet her before the World Cup' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/world-cup/2022/11/18/nathan-ake-interview-wife-had-baby-induced-early-could-meet/ |work=The Telegraph |date=18 November 2022 |access-date=21 November 2023 |archive-date=14 December 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241214032036/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/world-cup/2022/11/18/nathan-ake-interview-wife-had-baby-induced-early-could-meet/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

